<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910521-0019</DOCNO><DOCID>910521-0019.</DOCID><HL>   Sierra Semiconductor   Named in Patent Suit   Brought by Brooktree</HL><DATE>05/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   BTRE SERA</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)</RE><LP>   SAN DIEGO -- Brooktree Corp. said it filed suit againstSierra Semiconductor Corp., San Jose, Calif., charging thechip maker with patent infringement of Brooktree's videodigital-to-analog converter technology.   The suit, filed in federal court here, seeks a preliminaryinjunction barring Sierra from making and selling thecomputer-graphics products covered by the disputed patents.It also seeks a permanent injunction and unspecified damages.</LP><TEXT>   Jim Diller, Sierra's president, said in a statement thecompany is surprised by the suit, as it had not had anycontact with Brooktree over the patents before the complaintwas filed. Sierra's stock fell 75 cents to $15 inover-the-counter trading.   In 1990, Brooktree won $26 million in apatent-infringement case against Advanced Micro Devices Inc.of Sunnyvale, Calif., that involved two of the same patents.Advanced Micro, which is appealing the jury award, is alsosuing Brooktree in a separate patent-infringement case.</TEXT></DOC>